1 2. Assist individuals in attaining employment, education,
2 occupational training, or other means of supporting employment and
3 promoting self-sufficiency;
4 3. Assist in identifying and communicating gaps in current
5 community and health care resources; and
6 4. Build individual and community capacity by increasing health
7 knowledge and self-sufficiency through a range of activities such as
8 outreach, community education, coaching, mentoring, social support,
9 and advocacy, including efforts within faith-based settings.
10 C. In carrying out the functions described in paragraph 1 of
11 subsection B of this section, community health workers shall
12 emphasize available resources of private, nonprofit, or faith-based
13 organizations, and shall not rely solely on public assistance
14 programs for delivery of services.
15 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
16 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 2063d of Title 63, unless there
17 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
18 To be eligible for voluntary community health worker
19 certification, an individual shall:
20 1. Be a United States citizen or lawful permanent resident;
21 2. Be a resident of this state;
22 3. Be at least eighteen (18) years of age; and
